					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">439 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>274</height>
										<width>200</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>204</height>
										<width>130</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>439 folios (+ 3 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end); 1 paper leaf added after [iii recto].</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>44 quires of 10 leaves each, with catchwords at the end.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="20" writtenLines="20">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>All the biblical books begin a new page except Ecclesiastes and Esther.</p>
									<p>Numbers, Hafṭarot, Ruth and Song of Songs begin a new leaf.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary> Italian semi-cursive script, partially punctuated, of the 3rd quarter of the 15th century. <name type="person" role="scribe">Shemu᾿el</name>: inscribed with his name (190r). Decorated by the Florentine artists.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="patron">Yo᾿av Imanu᾿el Finzi</name>  (da Arezzo?): his coat of arms? (76v); it is identical with the coat of arms represented in Harley 5716 and 5717, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">544</ref> and <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">545</ref>, the patron of which was Yo᾿av Imanu᾿el. Thus the codex most probably was ordered by the same patron, Yo᾿av Imanu᾿el. </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Domenico Irosolimitano</name> (active 1575-1624): inscribed with his name, <date calendar="Gregorian">1598</date>  (439v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">62-74</ref>.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Giovanni Domenico Carretto</name>, Italian censor (active 1600-1624): inscribed with his name (439v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">100-101</ref>. </p>
							<p>Contents of manuscript in English ([533r]). </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p> 	Pre-1600. Dark brown, tooled, with remains of clasps.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1450" notAfter="1474"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Italy</name>, N. E. (<name type="place">Ferrara</name>?)</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name>: bought by him through <name type="person" role="bookseller">Nathaniel Noel </name>(b. 1681, d. 1753) (see <ref target="Wright_1966"/> and <ref target="Wright_1972"/>; inscription by Harley's librarian, Humfrey Wanley, <date calendar="Gregorian">18 January 1723/4</date> (folio 1r).</p>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts. Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date> to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
							<date>1753</date>
						</acquisition>
